<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900403-0171</DOCNO><DOCID>900403-0171.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Ivan Boesky to Complete   Prison Term, Be Released</HL><DATE>04/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Ivan F. Boesky will be a free man againtomorrow, when he is expected to be released from theBrooklyn, N.Y., halfway house where he is completing athree-year prison term.   Mr. Boesky, once one of the most powerful figures on WallStreet, stunned the financial world in November 1986 with theannouncement that he had agreed to plead guilty to one felonyand had settled Securities and Exchange Commission charges bypaying a record $100 million. He was sentenced to prison inDecember 1987.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Boesky's agreement to cooperate with the governmentled to the most sweeping investigations ever of thesecurities industry and insider trading.   Mr. Boesky began his term in a minimum security prison inLompoc, Calif., in March 1987. He was released to theBrooklyn halfway house last December, but because thefacility is overcrowded, he has been permitted to live athome and has had to check in regularly. With time off forgood behavior, he has served little more than two years ofhis sentence.   Mr. Boesky is expected to make his courtroom debut as agovernment witness as soon as next month, when the governmentwill try its case against John A. Mulheren Jr., anarbitrager. Mr. Mulheren was charged with taking stockpositions for Mr. Boesky to conceal the true ownership of thesecurities, a tactic known as stock &quot;parking.&quot; A lawyer forMr. Boesky said the former stock speculator didn't know whathe would next do for a living. But the attorney said Mr.Boesky isn't likely to return to the financial industry.</TEXT></DOC>